The article commemorates the 75th anniversary of the Battle of Iwo Jima, highlighting the sacrifices and heroism displayed by American forces during the battle. Despite American superiority in terms of aerial and naval power, the Japanese forces on the island were determined to defend their strategically important airfields. The battle lasted for five weeks and resulted in the death of nearly 7,000 Americans. The fighting on Iwo Jima was one of the bloodiest and costliest in World War II but also showcased acts of uncommon valor and patriotism. The iconic photo of six Marines raising the American flag atop Mount Suribachi became a symbol of the battle. Additionally, 27 Medals of Honor were awarded for acts of gallantry during the battle, with 22 of them going to Marines. The article also mentions Rabbi Roland Gittelsohn, who delivered a powerful message at the Fifth Marine Division cemetery, emphasizing the equality of all men and women regardless of race, religion, or creed. The article concludes by expressing gratitude to the Greatest Generation for their service and sacrifices.